[Gemini]: The `EmailValidator` class in `django/core/validators.py` contains two regular expressions, `user_regex` and `domain_regex`, both of which are vulnerable to ReDoS. I will analyze and submit a finding for `user_regex` first.

The `user_regex` is intended to validate the local part of an email address. It is composed of two parts, one for "dot-atom" strings and one for "quoted-string". The "dot-atom" part is vulnerable.

The regex is: `(^[-!#$%&'*+/=?^_`{}|~0-9A-Z]+(\\.[-!#$%&'*+/=?^_`{}|~0-9A-Z]+)*\\Z|...)`

The vulnerability lies in the pattern `(A+(B+)*)*`, specifically `[-!#$%&'*+/=?^_`{}|~0-9A-Z]+(\\.[-!#$%&'*+/=?^_`{}|~0-9A-Z]+)*`. The subpattern `(\\.[-!#$%&'*+/=?^_`{}|~0-9A-Z]+)*` contains a `+` quantifier inside a `*` quantifier. This structure can lead to catastrophic backtracking when the regex engine processes certain inputs.

An attacker can provide a string like `"a.a.a.a.a.a.a.a.a.a@example.com"`. The repeated `a.` sequence can be matched in multiple ways by the regex engine, causing it to explore an exponential number of paths and leading to a CPU spike that can render the application unresponsive.

I will now submit this finding.

